{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17519493","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17519493"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T14:12:26+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T14:12:26+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13030"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"13030","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13030"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.22,0.69,0.03,0.02,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5467"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"37205"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"5467","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/5467"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13030"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"21860"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"12"},{"type":"tags","id":"34"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"1903"},{"type":"tags","id":"2843"},{"type":"tags","id":"2852"},{"type":"tags","id":"4974"},{"type":"tags","id":"5810"},{"type":"tags","id":"11633"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"9274"},{"type":"contributions","id":"9356"},{"type":"contributions","id":"15808"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43381"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"37205","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/37205"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 61-year-old man presents with a two day history of pain in his left knee. He does not have any other symptoms, such as any fevers, chills or night sweats, and there is no history of any trauma to the knee. He has had some vague abdominal pain and constipation recently. His history includes hypertension and type 2 diabetes mellitus (T2DM). He is a reformed smoker and drinks about three glasses of wine a day. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination his blood pressure is 136/82 mmHg, pulse 84/min and temperature 37.4\u003Csup\u003Eo\u003C/sup\u003EC. His BMI is 32. There is marked swelling of the left knee, with erythema and localised tenderness.  Laboratory findings reveal an elevated calcium level (2.9 mmol/L). A joint aspiration is performed and the synovial fluid sent for analysis.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is most likely to be seen on analysis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Negatively birefringent needle-shaped crystals","Positively birefringent rhomboid-shaped crystals","Neutrophil predominance with gram-positive cocci","Negatively birefringent needle-shaped crystals AND gram-positive cocci","Normal synovial fluid findings"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient has hypercalcaemia, which in the absence of any other obvious precipitating cause could be due to secondary to hyperparathyroidism and an underlying parathyroid adenoma. Patients with hypercalcaemia are at risk for developing pseudogout, a rheumatological disease with diverse symptoms and signs arising from the accumulation of calcium pyrophosphate dihydrate crystals in the connective tissues. It commonly presents with acute onset, painful monoarthropathy of the knee.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPositively birefringent rhomboid-shaped crystals \u003C/strong\u003Eare indicative of calcium pyrophosphate dihydrate crystals, also known as pseudogout. Pseudogout is a condition where these crystals deposit in the joint, causing inflammation and pain. Given the patient\u0027s presentation and elevated calcium level, this is the most likely diagnosis. Joint aspiration with synovial fluid analysis confirms the diagnosis, showing rhomboid-shaped crystals that are positively birefringent.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENegatively birefringent needle-shaped crystals\u003C/strong\u003E describe characteristic of monosodium urate crystals seen in gout, which also presents with acute onset monoarthropathy, but usually affects the first metatarsophalangeal joint of the foot. Furthermore, gout is not triggered by hypercalcaemia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENeutrophil predominance with gram-positive cocci \u003C/strong\u003Eis a finding that suggests a septic arthritis, which is characterised by joint infection. However, the clinical presentation in this case does not strongly support a joint infection, and the elevated calcium level is more consistent with pseudogout.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENegatively birefringent needle-shaped crystals AND gram-positive cocci\u003C/strong\u003E combines features of gout (negatively birefringent needle-shaped crystals) and a septic joint (gram-positive cocci). However, the presentation and laboratory findings in this case are more suggestive of pseudogout rather than gout or a septic joint.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENormal synovial fluid findings\u003C/strong\u003E are not the normal in the setting of pseudogout. Given the patient\u0027s symptoms, physical examination findings, and laboratory results (elevated calcium level), it is unlikely that the synovial fluid analysis would show normal findings.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["After an appropriate physical examination, patients suspected to have calcium pyrophosphate deposition disease should undergo arthrocentesis for synovial fluid analysis, in addition to radiography of the involved joints.","Diagnostic confirmation may be via the presence of rhomboid crystals in the synovial fluid aspirate visualized under polarized microscopy."],"references":["Zamora EA, Naik R. Calcium Pyrophosphate Deposition Disease. [Updated 2023 Jan 27]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2023 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK540151/","Rho YH, Zhu Y, Zhang Y, Reginato AM, Choi HK. Risk factors for pseudogout in the general population. Rheumatology (Oxford). 2012 Nov;51(11):2070-4. doi: 10.1093/rheumatology/kes204. Epub 2012 Aug 11. PMID: 22886340; PMCID: PMC3475980."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"21860"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13030"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"21860","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/21860"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2023-06-24T11:03:08+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-09-22T20:07:08+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5467"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"37205"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"12","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/12"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc4b","name":"Rheumatology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:47+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"34","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/34"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddb4","name":"Orthopaedics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"65","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/65"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Investigations","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":nu